Nominalists say they know this disjunctively: it is either A or B or C, &a But this is an idle quibble: to know thus disjunctively is not to know (p. 26, l. 31 to end; p. 27, l. 1 to 20). “

Now all this looks to modern readers —— and since they are modern, they must os course be in the right — very much like mere loss of time and trouble; useless expenditure of braia-work.
